---
/** Hub: gig unit economics. Worked example by gigUnitEconomics(). */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import GigIncomeCalculator from '../../components/calculators/GigIncomeCalculator.tsx';
import { gigUnitEconomics } from '../../lib/gig-economics';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = gigUnitEconomics(20000, 500, 4000, 4000, 500);
---

<Base
  title="Gig income calculator 2026 — what an hour really pays"
  description="See what your gig work actually pays per hour and per mile after the mileage deduction and a tax set-aside — the number the app's gross earnings hide."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">Gig economy</p>
    <h1>Gig income calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">The app shows gross. This shows what an hour is worth after mileage and taxes.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    A rideshare or delivery app tells you what you earned, not what you made. Every
    mile costs gas and wear, and no one withholds your taxes. This works out your
    real net profit, what an hour and a mile pay once the mileage deduction comes
    out, and what is left after setting aside for tax.
  </p>

  <GigIncomeCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — {formatMoney(20000)} over 500 hours</h2>
  <p>
    A driver earns {formatMoney(20000)} across 500 hours, driving 8,000 business
    miles, with {formatMoney(500)} of other costs:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Measure</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Gross per hour</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.grossPerHour)}/hr</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mileage deduction (a real cost)</td><td>− {formatMoney(ex.mileageDeduction)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Net profit</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.netProfit)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Net per hour</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.netPerHour)}/hr</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Take-home per hour after a 30% tax set-aside</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.afterSetAsidePerHour)}/hr</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The app's {formatMoney(ex.grossPerHour)} an hour becomes {formatMoney(ex.netPerHour)}
    once mileage is counted, and about {formatMoney(ex.afterSetAsidePerHour)} once you
    set aside for taxes. That gap is why the headline rate is misleading — the miles
    are a cost even when the standard deduction, not cash, is how you claim them.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Why count the mileage deduction as a cost?</h3>
    <p>
      Because driving really does cost money — fuel, tires, maintenance, the car
      wearing out. The IRS standard mileage rate (72.5¢ then 76¢ in 2026) is a fair
      proxy for that per-mile cost, so subtracting it shows your true profit, and it
      is also exactly what you deduct on Schedule C.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How much should I set aside for taxes?</h3>
    <p>
      Around 25–35% of net profit for self-employment tax (15.3%) plus federal and
      state income tax. This calculator uses 30% as a middle estimate. For a precise
      figure by state, use the <a href="/1099-tax-calculator/">1099 tax calculator</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Which miles count?</h3>
    <p>
      Miles driven for the work — between deliveries, waiting for the next ping while
      logged on, driving to a busy zone. Commuting from home to where you start is
      not deductible. Track them with an app; the deduction is too large to estimate.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is a low net-per-hour normal?</h3>
    <p>
      For driving gigs, often yes — the mileage cost is high. If your net-per-hour is
      well below local wages, it can mean you are driving too far for each job, or a
      less efficient car is eating the margin. The
      <a href="/vehicle-cost-calculator/">vehicle cost calculator</a> shows your real
      per-mile cost.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/mileage-deduction-calculator/">Mileage deduction calculator</a> — the 2026 split rate</li>
    <li><a href="/vehicle-cost-calculator/">Vehicle cost calculator</a> — your real cost per mile</li>
    <li><a href="/gig-tax-calculator/">Gig tax by category</a> — driver, seller, creator and more</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Economics estimate for the 2026 tax year, before the exact tax on the profit.
    Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
